<h1>HONR Network - Sandy Hook</h1>
<p>&nbsp;HONR Network is a registered 501(c)(3) non-profit corporation based in Florida. As a public charity, it is exempt from federal income taxes under U.S. law. Its Tax ID number is #82-3556040. The organization was created with a mission to protect, support, and advocate for individuals and families who face harassment and abuse online.</p><div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"><a href="https://honrnetwork.org/honr-timeline/" ><img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjwjrEGscJE585xd4gQjaEa0VtukiQg-BRUC9yPRDh44qdzHG_dWL4PNI4JLcfzE3fHPY7r6WAlNURYBpV7uh56YE00MOtxxu-20Zsq-t1EN307qnCcbHXb1iXMuP95X3-5lOsxFfTc-KgUKJp7KIh7OpxlCFDMI4tWzk4XcUX8yNL-37dfKlL_ooxsXjXN/s16000/1_mLFYgFm71oTVKa3LOQZFoA.webp" /></a></div>
<p>&nbsp;The HONR Network was founded by Lenny Pozner after the tragic Sandy Hook massacre. Initially, its purpose was to stop the ongoing harassment and emotional torment faced by the families of victims who became targets of online hate and hoax campaigns. Over time, as other mass-casualty events occurred and more families sought help, the organization expanded its mission to support anyone affected by online harassment and abuse. Today, the HONR Network works to provide education, guidance, and advocacy to victims, professionals, and policymakers to create a safer and more inclusive internet environment.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Since its creation, the HONR Network has played a crucial role in removing tens of thousands of harmful and illegal pieces of online content, including posts, videos, and images designed to harass or intimidate victims and their families. The organization assists victims of various forms of cybercrime such as harassment, revenge porn, and stalking, offering removal support and guidance. In addition, HONR Network collaborates with major social media companies to improve reporting systems, enhance removal processes, and develop better policies to protect victims—particularly in the immediate aftermath of violent or highly publicized events when they are most vulnerable.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Lenny Pozner has also pursued legal action against harassers and hoaxers, helping to establish legal precedents that make it easier for other victims of online abuse to hold offenders accountable in court. These efforts not only bring justice but also strengthen the framework for online safety and protection.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The HONR Network operates as a non-partisan organization, independent of any political party or affiliation. Its members and volunteers represent diverse political views, unified by a shared goal of combating online hate. While the organization was born out of the attacks on the Sandy Hook victims’ families, it does not affiliate with any other Sandy Hook-related charities or external causes. Individual board members may participate in their own philanthropic or political initiatives, but these activities are separate from the HONR Network’s work.</p>
<p>&nbsp;The statistics featured on the HONR Network website come from credible and respected sources in addition to its own internal data. These include research from the Pew Research Center, Data & Society Research Institute, Fight the New Drug, The Washington Post, the A. James Clark School of Engineering, and other institutions that study online harassment and digital abuse.</p><a id="dynamicLink" href="" style="font-size:24px"></a>
